<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="284" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[303,1697,1884,2128]" pageId="1" pageNumber="284">
Diagnosis: Stenopogonine flies with the following combination of characters: Antenna with well-developed microsegment; ﬁrst ﬁagcllomere longer than scape and pedicel combined; propleuron and lateral lobes of pronotum equipped with strong welldeveloped bristles (
<figureCitation box="[619,708,2007,2043]" captionStart="Figs 1-5" captionStartId="3.[296,351,2402,2434]" captionTargetBox="[271,1731,380,2363]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-5. Anasillomas chıysopos spec. nov. paratype male. 1. Antenna, lateral aspect. 2. Head and part of thorax. 3-5. Genitalia. 3. Lateral. 4. Ventral. 5. Dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4030762" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4030762/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="284">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
): palps at least half as long as proboscis; facial swellìng not markedly projecting in dorsal part (Fig. a); Cell 
<emphasis box="[1121,1148,2062,2085]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="284">m</emphasis>
, narrowly open on wing margin; dorsocentral bristles poorly developed anterior of transverse suture.
</paragraph>
